\begin{abstract}
We give sufficient conditions for the number rigidity of a translation invariant or periodic point process on ${\mathbb{R}}^d$, where $d=1,2$. That is, the probability distribution of the number of particles in a bounded domain ${\Lambda} \subset {\mathbb{R}}^d$, conditional on the configuration on ${\Lambda}^{\complement}$, is concentrated on a single integer $N_{\Lambda}$. These conditions are : (a) the variance of the  number of particles in a bounded domain ${\Omega} \subset {\mathbb{R}}^d$ grows slower than the volume of ${\Omega}$ (a.k.a. superhomogeneous  point processes), when ${\Omega} \uparrow {\mathbb{R}}^d$ (in a self-similar manner), and (b) the truncated pair correlation function is bounded by $C_1[|x-y|+1]^{-2}$ in $d=1$ and by $C_2[|x-y|+1]^{-(4+{\varepsilon})}$ in $d=2$. These conditions are satisfied by all known processes with number rigidity [\cite{GP},\cite{G},\cite{PS},\cite{AM},\cite{Bu},\cite{BuDQ}], \cite{BBNY}, and many more. in $d=1,2$. We also observe, in the light of the results of \cite{PS}, that no such criteria exist in $d>2$.
\end{abstract}



\section{Introduction}

Point processes on ${\mathbb{R}}^d$ (or ${\boldsymbol{Z}}^d$) are measures $\mu({\mathrm{d}} X)$ giving rise to consistent probability measures $\mu_{\Lambda}$ on
configurations of particles $X_{{\Lambda}}$ on all regions ${\Lambda} \subset {\mathbb{R}}^d$ (or ${\boldsymbol{Z}}^d$). When the volume of ${\Lambda}$, denoted $|{\Lambda}|$, is finite, this probability is concentrated on configurations $X_{\Lambda}=\{x_1,\cdots,x_N; x_l \in {\Lambda}\}$, $N$ finite. From $\mu ({\mathrm{d}} X)$, we can find the conditional probabilities $\mu({\mathrm{d}} X_{\Lambda} | {\Lambda}^{\complement})$ of configurations in ${\Lambda}$, given the configuration in ${\Lambda}^{\complement} = {\mathbb{R}}^d \setminus {\Lambda}$. We shall always assume that $\mu$ is ergodic and either translation invariant or periodic.





The simplest example of a point process on ${\mathbb{R}}^d$ is the translation invariant Poisson process with density (intensity) $\rho>0$. For this process, there is no information gained about $X_{\Lambda}$ from knowing about $X_{{\Lambda}^{\complement}}$, so $\mu({\mathrm{d}} X_{\Lambda} | X_{{\Lambda}^{\complement}})=\mu({\mathrm{d}} X_{\Lambda})$. In general, for equilibrium systems with sufficiently rapidly decaying (tempered) interaction potentials $U(X)$, the infinite volume Gibbs measures, $\mu_{\mathrm{eq}}$, describe a point process whose conditional probabilities satisfy the DLR (Dobrushin, Lanford, Ruelle) equation

text:
\begin{equation} 
\label{DLR}
 \mu_{\mathrm{eq}} ({\mathrm{d}} X_{\Lambda} | X_{{\Lambda}^{\complement}})  = \exp [ - {\beta} U(X_{\Lambda} | X_{{\Lambda}^{\complement}})  ] \bigg/ \left ( \int_{\Lambda} \exp(-{\beta} U(X_{\Lambda} | X_{{\Lambda}^{\complement}})) {\mathrm{d}} X_{\Lambda}\right),
\end{equation}

nexttext:


Note that for point processes satisying the DLR equation (and some other mild conditions), the variance of the number of particles in ${\Lambda}$ (denoted $N_{\Lambda}$) is bounded below by $c|{\Lambda}|, c>0$, for ${\beta}$ finite (\cite{Gi-1},\cite{LPRS}). Such processes are therefore not superhomogeneous and also not rigid for finite ${\beta}$. 


